hivis.data

Interface DataTable

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Data, DataMap<String,DataSeries<?>>, Iterable<DataRow>
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    TableView
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractDataTable, AbstractTableView, AbstractUnmodifiableDataTable, DataTableDefault, SortedTable, TableViewAppend, TableViewFilterRows, TableViewFunction, TableViewSeries, TableViewSeriesBase, TableViewTranspose

    public interface DataTable
extends DataMap<String,DataSeries<?>>, Iterable<DataRow>

    Represents a table of data in which the columns are represented as DataSeries, each of which has a unique String label. The label/series pairs have a fixed order (either the order they have been added or an ordering defined by a view).

    DataTable extends DataMap, it's a mapping from labels to DataSeries, this means that it inherits several methods which are awkwardly named in the context of a table, such as DataMap.keys() (series labels) and DataMap.values() (corresponding data series). On the plus side these methods provide the set of labels and series as view DataSeries that will update when labels/series are added, removed or rearranged in the table.

    Author:
    O. J. Coleman

      • selectSeriesRE

        TableView selectSeriesRE(Pattern pattern,
                         String renamePattern)
        Get a view of this table containing the series whose labels match the given regular expression, renaming the series with the given rename pattern.
        Parameters:
        pattern - The regular expression pattern to use to match series labels.
        renamePattern - The replacement pattern (with $N referring to capture groups in 'pattern'). If renamePattern contains '\\oi' or '\\ni' it will be replaced by the original or new index of the series respectively. An '\\oi' or '\\ni' may be followed by numerals to indicate an offset, for example "my\\ni5pf" will give strings "my5pf", my6pf", "my7pf" and so on.
        Returns:
        a view of this table containing the specified series in the order they appear in this table, renamed according the renamePattern.

      • relabelSeriesPP

        TableView relabelSeriesPP(String prefix,
                          String postfix)
        Get a view of this table containing the series in this table renamed by prepending and appending the specified prefix and postfix to the labels. If the prefix or postfix contain '\\oi' this will be replaced by the (original) index of the series. An '\\oi' may be followed by numerals to indicate an offset, for example "my\\oi5pf" will give strings "my5pf", my6pf", "my7pf" and so on.
        Parameters:
        prefix - The string to prepend to each label. May be null or an empty string.
        postfix - The string to append to each label. May be null or an empty string.

      • sort

        TableView sort(int sortingSeries)

        Create a view of this table containing the rows in this table sorted into ascending order, according to the natural ordering of the values in the specified series.

        All values in the specified series must implement the Comparable interface. Furthermore, all values must be mutually comparable (that is, v1.compareTo(v2) must not throw a ClassCastException for any values v1 and v2). (This is the case for all numeric, string and date values.)

        This sort is guaranteed to be stable: equal values will not be reordered as a result of the sort.

        Throws:
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the sortingSeries index is out of range ( index < 0 || index >= seriesCount())

      • sort

        TableView sort(String sortingSeries)

        Create a view of this table containing the rows in this table sorted into ascending order, according to the natural ordering of the values in the specified series.

        All values in the specified series must implement the Comparable interface. Furthermore, all values must be mutually comparable (that is, v1.compareTo(v2) must not throw a ClassCastException for any values v1 and v2). (This is the case for all numeric, string and date values.)

        This sort is guaranteed to be stable: equal values will not be reordered as a result of the sort.

        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if there is no series with the given sortingSeries label.

      • sort

        TableView sort(Comparator<DataRow> comparator)

        Create a view of this table containing the rows in this table sorted according to the order induced by the specified comparator. The comparator must accept any two DataRows from this table and determine their relative ordering according to the contract specified by Comparator

        This sort is guaranteed to be stable: equal rows, according to the comparator, will not be reordered as a result of the sort.

      • group

        <K> GroupedTable<K> group(int groupingSeries)

        Create a view of this table containing the rows in the table grouped according to the values in the specified series. The grouping is represented as a GroupedTable. Groups are formed by placing all rows for which getRow(x).get(groupingSeries).equals(getRow(y).get(groupingSeries)), for all rows x and y, into the same group (and rows where this is false into different groups). The key for each group is a value such that key.equals(group.getRow(z).get(groupingSeries)) for all rows z in the group.

        The rows in the group table views appear in the same order as their order in this table.

        See GroupedTable for more information.

        Throws:
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the groupingSeries index is out of range ( index < 0 || index >= seriesCount())

      • group

        <K> GroupedTable<K> group(String groupingSeries)

        Create a view of this table containing the rows in the table grouped according to the values in the specified series. The grouping is represented as a GroupedTable. Groups are formed by placing all rows for which getRow(x).get(groupingSeries).equals(getRow(y).get(groupingSeries)), for all rows x and y, into the same group (and rows where this is false into different groups). The key for each group is a value such that key.equals(group.getRow(z).get(groupingSeries)) for all rows z in the group.

        The rows in the group table views appear in the same order as their order in this table.

        See GroupedTable for more information.

        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if there is no series with the given groupingSeries label.

      • group

        <K> GroupedTable<K> group(Function<DataRow,K> rowKeyFunction)

        Create a view of this table containing the rows in the table grouped according to the specified row key function. The grouping is represented as a GroupedTable. The key for a row is calculated using the given row key function, which should accept a row from the table and return a group key (identifier) for that row. Groups are formed by placing all rows for which rowKeyFunction(getRow(x)).equals(rowKeyFunction(getRow(y)), for all rows x and y, into the same group (and rows where this is false into different groups). The key for each group is a value such that key.equals(rowKeyFunction(group.getRow(z)) for all rows z in the group table.

        The rows in the group table views appear in the same order as their order in this table.

        See GroupedTable for more information.

      • apply

        TableView apply(SeriesFunction<?,?> function)
        Get a table containing the series in this table passed through the given SeriesFunction. The series labels remain unchanged. The function must be able to handle each series in this table. If series are added or removed from this series it will be reflected in the returned table. If values change in the series in this table the changes will be reflected in the series in the returned table (as applicable according to the function).
        Parameters:
        function - The function to generate the series for the new table.
        Returns:
        a table containing series generated by applying the given function to each series in this table.

      • toRange

        TableView toRange(double min,
                  double max)
        Get a view of this table in which the numeric series are scaled to the specified range. For example if a series contains the values [5, 25, 11, 16] and toRange(0, 10) is called on it the resulting series will contain (0, 10, 3, 5.5).
        Parameters:
        min - The minimum value of the range.
        max - The maximum value of the range.
        See Also:
        DataSeries.toRange(double, double)

      • toRange

        TableView toRange(DataValue<?> min,
                  DataValue<?> max)
        Get a view of this table in which the numeric series are scaled to the specified range. For example if a series contains the values [5, 25, 11, 16] and toRange(0, 10) is called on it the resulting series will contain (0, 10, 3, 5.5).
        Parameters:
        min - The minimum value of the range. Changes to this DataValue will be reflected in the returned table.
        max - The maximum value of the range. Changes to this DataValue will be reflected in the returned table.
        See Also:

      • transpose

        TableView transpose()
        Get a transposed view of this table. If a row key series is set in this table and it contains no duplicate values it will be used for the series labels in the transposed table, otherwise the row indices will be used for the series labels in the transposed table (see setRowKey(int)). The series labels for this table will become the row key in the transposed table.

      • combine

        TableView combine(DataTable table)
        Get a table view comprising the series in this table followed by the series in the given table. The returned table will have this.seriesCount() + table.seriesCount() series.
        Parameters:
        table - The table to combine with this table.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - If this table and the given table contain any series with the same labels.

      • append

        TableView append(DataTable table)
        Get a table view comprising the series in the given table appended to the series in this table. The returned table will have the same number of series as this (and the given) table, but the length will be this.length() + table.length().
        Parameters:
        table - The table to append. It must have series with the same labels in the same order as this table.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - If the series labels (both presence and order) or types do not match.
